"Continuity of Solutions
of Parabolic and Elliptic

00:42:42.230 --> 00:42:43.930
Equations," by John Nash.

00:42:43.930 --> 00:42:47.740
And now you understand
what it was about.

00:42:47.740 --> 00:42:54.360
1958, 24 pages-- rather short.

00:42:54.360 --> 00:42:59.560
By current standards,
very short.

00:42:59.560 --> 00:43:01.870
It's interesting to read
what he thought about this.

00:43:01.870 --> 00:43:04.330
"The open problems in the
area of nonlinear partial

00:43:04.330 --> 00:43:07.290
differential equations are very
relevant to applied mathematics

00:43:07.290 --> 00:43:09.970
and science as a
whole, perhaps more so

00:43:09.970 --> 00:43:13.220
than the open problems in any
other area of mathematics,

00:43:13.220 --> 00:43:16.380
and this field seems poised
for rapid development.

00:43:16.380 --> 00:43:20.300
It seems clear, however, that
fresh methods must be employed.

00:43:20.300 --> 00:43:23.180
We hope this paper contributes
significantly in this way

00:43:23.180 --> 00:43:26.310
and also that the new methods
used in our previous paper

00:43:26.310 --> 00:43:27.480
will be of value."

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:31.210
That was absolutely true.

00:43:31.210 --> 00:43:33.550
"Little is known about
the existence, uniqueness,

00:43:33.550 --> 00:43:37.040
and smoothness of solutions of
the general equations of flow

00:43:37.040 --> 00:43:40.070
of a viscous, compressible,
and heat-conducting fluid."

00:43:40.070 --> 00:43:41.950
It's still true.

00:43:41.950 --> 00:43:44.450
Almost 50 years
after what he wrote,

00:43:44.450 --> 00:43:50.760
we are still in the dark about
some basic features about this.

00:43:50.760 --> 00:43:53.950
The style was informal and
informative-- very interesting.

00:43:53.950 --> 00:43:56.930
You know, he doesn't suggest
this and that and that.

00:43:56.930 --> 00:43:59.650
He also says about key results.

00:43:59.650 --> 00:44:03.360
Also tells you what he
had to work hard on.

00:44:03.360 --> 00:44:05.990
And he also says things
like "This is dimensionally

00:44:05.990 --> 00:44:09.050
the only possible form for
a bound"-- reasoning a bit

00:44:09.050 --> 00:44:10.520
like a physicist.

00:44:10.520 --> 00:44:13.190
He speaks of "dynamic
inequalities."

00:44:13.190 --> 00:44:15.180
What does it mean, a
"dynamic inequality"?

00:44:15.180 --> 00:44:17.300
Well, you know, it's to
convey some impression.

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:18.560
It's precious.

00:44:18.560 --> 00:44:21.580
Or "powerful
inequality"-- et cetera.

00:44:21.580 --> 00:44:24.170
"The methods here were
used by physical intuition,

00:44:24.170 --> 00:44:26.140
but the ritual of
mathematical expression

00:44:26.140 --> 00:44:29.760
tends to hide this
natural basis."

00:44:29.760 --> 00:44:34.100
He doesn't want just people
to see right through.

00:44:34.100 --> 00:44:37.120
He wants them to understand
how he got into this.

00:44:37.120 --> 00:44:40.020
Very generously, actually.

00:44:40.020 --> 00:44:42.300
The notions were unexpected.

00:44:42.300 --> 00:44:45.010
He was thinking of the solution
of the heat equation in terms

00:44:45.010 --> 00:44:47.910
of statistical mechanics,
with temperature

00:44:47.910 --> 00:44:49.940
being like density of matter.

00:44:49.940 --> 00:44:53.350
As if there was such a
thing as atoms of heat.

00:44:53.350 --> 00:44:55.490
Doesn't exist, the atom of heat.

00:44:55.490 --> 00:44:59.220
But let's think
like it's this way.

00:44:59.220 --> 00:45:01.970
And he used the entropy
solution of disorder

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:04.610
used by Boltzmann,
and later by Shannon,

00:45:04.610 --> 00:45:07.600
to measure the disorder
or microscopic uncertainty

00:45:07.600 --> 00:45:09.620
of that temperature.

00:45:09.620 --> 00:45:12.060
From physical point
of view, this quantity

00:45:12.060 --> 00:45:15.670
minus integral of T
log T makes no sense.

00:45:15.670 --> 00:45:19.600
It would make sense, you
know, if T was, like,

00:45:19.600 --> 00:45:22.110
a density of matter.

00:45:22.110 --> 00:45:24.020
But there's no such
thing, as I said,

00:45:24.020 --> 00:45:27.906
as matter-- as a particular
associated to temperature.

00:45:27.906 --> 00:45:30.220
But it works.

00:45:30.220 --> 00:45:32.910
In a radically unusual context.

00:45:32.910 --> 00:45:37.090
And he used this
notion in a context

00:45:37.090 --> 00:45:41.770
which is very different from
the one it was introduced for.

00:45:41.770 --> 00:45:43.630
And he demonstrated,
with his proof,

00:45:43.630 --> 00:45:46.940
the power of differential
inequalities,

00:45:46.940 --> 00:45:51.610
that these inequalities between
slopes of various quantities,

00:45:51.610 --> 00:45:54.580
involving simple quantities
containing information,

00:45:54.580 --> 00:45:57.420
in some sense.

00:45:57.420 --> 00:46:00.540
It was, a bit, the same
amazement as the one that

00:46:00.540 --> 00:46:04.820
Grigori Perelman, again, would
generate when he showed that,

00:46:04.820 --> 00:46:07.770
to solve the Poincare
problem of geometry,

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:10.170
it was useful to
introduce some entropy. .

00:46:13.300 --> 00:46:15.720
This was a masterpiece
in several parts.

00:46:15.720 --> 00:46:20.360
Let me not go into details
but very rapidly say

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:23.390
that it was like first act
was about understanding

00:46:23.390 --> 00:46:25.820
displacement of what
would be something

00:46:25.820 --> 00:46:28.150
like an atomic sort of heat.

00:46:28.150 --> 00:46:32.410
Like a Brownian motion, like
a particle of temperature.

00:46:32.410 --> 00:46:34.130
And, through them,
the temperature

00:46:34.130 --> 00:46:37.610
was neither too
low nor too strong.

00:46:37.610 --> 00:46:40.360
That contributions of
sources of temperature

00:46:40.360 --> 00:46:42.490
would overlap, in some sense.

00:46:42.490 --> 00:46:44.180
That, if two point
sources are closed,

00:46:44.180 --> 00:46:45.800
then the resulting
heat distributions

00:46:45.800 --> 00:46:48.520
are closed too, and
the decontinuity.

00:46:48.520 --> 00:46:54.090
And each of these steps has
precise mathematical statement.

00:46:54.090 --> 00:46:57.000
You know, in the
ideal of mathematics

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:00.840
the Holy Grail is to have
a nice, beautiful proof.

00:47:00.840 --> 00:47:05.000
And we get this concept as a
legacy of the Ancient Greeks,

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:06.780
and geometry in particular.

00:47:06.780 --> 00:47:08.710
This implies this
from that, et cetera.

00:47:08.710 --> 00:47:11.420
They like playing with this,
but the-- like, the bricks

00:47:11.420 --> 00:47:12.770
are not triangles and lines.

00:47:12.770 --> 00:47:14.684
These are, like,
qualitative properties

00:47:14.684 --> 00:47:15.725
of the heat distribution.

00:47:18.292 --> 00:47:19.750
Let me skip this,
even though these

00:47:19.750 --> 00:47:21.860
were some of the inequalities.

00:47:21.860 --> 00:47:26.420
And let's focus on
one thing, here.

00:47:26.420 --> 00:47:29.470
You see, what is written
here is Nash's inequality,

00:47:29.470 --> 00:47:32.290
in the middle of this slide.

00:47:32.290 --> 00:47:35.756
Everybody in analysis knows
this is Nash's inequality.

00:47:35.756 --> 00:47:37.130
Truth is-- and
it's clear, if you

00:47:37.130 --> 00:47:41.630
read the paper by Nash-- Nash
did not prove this inequality.

00:47:41.630 --> 00:47:44.880
He asked one of his
colleagues, named Stein,

00:47:44.880 --> 00:47:46.550
to prove the inequality.

00:47:46.550 --> 00:47:48.880
Stein was an expert in
this kind of things.

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:50.061
You want this inequality?

00:47:50.061 --> 00:47:50.560
Yeah.

00:47:50.560 --> 00:47:51.650
Let me prove it for you.

00:47:51.650 --> 00:47:52.730
Here is how you do it.

00:47:52.730 --> 00:47:53.930
Thank you.

00:47:53.930 --> 00:47:56.440
And Nash showed how to use
it in that problem of heat

00:47:56.440 --> 00:47:57.980
distribution.

00:47:57.980 --> 00:48:04.330
He was genius in this kind of
integrating the various parts.

00:48:04.330 --> 00:48:06.360
And of on.

00:48:06.360 --> 00:48:08.804
Let's skip this-- also this.

00:48:08.804 --> 00:48:10.220
He got from another
guy, actually,

00:48:10.220 --> 00:48:13.780
this one, from his colleague
Carlson, who introduced him

00:48:13.780 --> 00:48:17.750
to the concept of entropy
after he had studied that

00:48:17.750 --> 00:48:20.460
from his colleague [INAUDIBLE],
who had been specialist

00:48:20.460 --> 00:48:21.450
of Boltzmann equation.

00:48:21.450 --> 00:48:24.120
That was the style of Nash,
taking this idea here,

00:48:24.120 --> 00:48:25.250
that idea there.

00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:26.710
Mmm-- I think they are linked.

00:48:26.710 --> 00:48:27.530
I will use them.

00:48:27.530 --> 00:48:28.704
And so on.

00:48:28.704 --> 00:48:29.495
This was brilliant.

00:48:33.150 --> 00:48:36.080
[INAUDIBLE] Hollywood
and movie, after that

00:48:36.080 --> 00:48:37.550
would be the big celebration.

00:48:37.550 --> 00:48:40.670
I don't know-- Nash would have
married a beautiful heroine

00:48:40.670 --> 00:48:42.170
or whatever.

00:48:42.170 --> 00:48:44.640
It was not this way.

00:48:44.640 --> 00:48:46.840
The celebration was lost.

00:48:46.840 --> 00:48:50.680
In 1957, Nash heard that
a young, unknown Italian

00:48:50.680 --> 00:48:53.550
mathematician, Ennio de
Giorgi, proved the same result

00:48:53.550 --> 00:48:56.220
by a different method.

00:48:56.220 --> 00:49:01.560
To all mathematicians, this
would become as the, you know,

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:05.490
schoolbook example,
textbook case,

00:49:05.490 --> 00:49:08.920
of simultaneous discovery--
by different people,

00:49:08.920 --> 00:49:11.240
at the same time, with
different methods.

00:49:11.240 --> 00:49:13.430
Di Giorgi was completely
unknown at that time.

00:49:13.430 --> 00:49:16.310
He was eccentric, he was
monachal, he was genius.

00:49:16.310 --> 00:49:18.820
He would become a living legend.

00:49:18.820 --> 00:49:23.390
His proofs set the standard
for generations of experts.

00:49:23.390 --> 00:49:25.900
Nash, in spite of
being so bright,

00:49:25.900 --> 00:49:28.320
was in pathological
need of recognition

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:29.980
and attributed to
this coincident

00:49:29.980 --> 00:49:32.390
his failure to get
the 1958 Fields

00:49:32.390 --> 00:49:35.500
Medal, which went to French
mathematician Rene Thom.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:42.080
The epilogue was sinister.

00:49:42.080 --> 00:49:45.360
Nash's paper was accepted in
Acta Mathematica, arguably

00:49:45.360 --> 00:49:49.050
the best journal in the
world, in those days-- maybe

00:49:49.050 --> 00:49:51.040
nowadays, also.

00:49:51.040 --> 00:49:54.170
And after it was
accepted he withdrew it.

00:49:54.170 --> 00:49:56.110
Which is unheard of,
you know, if your paper

00:49:56.110 --> 00:49:58.760
is accepted in such a
journal, to withdraw it.

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:02.280
And he sent it to the American
Journal of Mathematics-- maybe

00:50:02.280 --> 00:50:04.730
the most famous paper in the
history of American Journal

00:50:04.730 --> 00:50:08.810
of Mathematics-- in the hope
of getting the Bocher prize,

00:50:08.810 --> 00:50:14.130
1959, a prize which had to go
to a paper published in there.

00:50:14.130 --> 00:50:15.550
OK.

00:50:15.550 --> 00:50:16.570
In vain.

00:50:16.570 --> 00:50:20.030
It was Nirenberg who
got the prize that year!

00:50:20.030 --> 00:50:22.110
For some other work.

00:50:22.110 --> 00:50:24.010
Hmm!

00:50:24.010 --> 00:50:27.320
Nash actually is already
undergoing paranoid delirium

00:50:27.320 --> 00:50:30.350
in there-- the start
of a long tragedy

00:50:30.350 --> 00:50:35.490
and more than two decades
of going mental hospital,

00:50:35.490 --> 00:50:39.650
at times, having some relapse
and some clear thoughts,

00:50:39.650 --> 00:50:42.760
at other times being
completely miserable-- haunting

00:50:42.760 --> 00:50:48.220
the corridors of Princeton,
talking nonsense, whatever.

00:50:48.220 --> 00:50:50.285
Meanwhile his papers will
make their revolution.

00:50:52.930 --> 00:50:55.640
To Louis Nirenberg, in
1980, somebody asked,

00:50:55.640 --> 00:50:58.110
do you know mathematicians
that you can consider geniuses?

00:50:58.110 --> 00:51:00.390
And Nirenberg answered
"I can think only of one,

00:51:00.390 --> 00:51:03.080
and that's John Nash."

00:51:03.080 --> 00:51:08.500
In 2011, to a young, brilliant
Princeton mathematician,

00:51:08.500 --> 00:51:11.105
John Pardon, somebody
in an interview

00:51:11.105 --> 00:51:13.480
asked, who is your favorite
Princetonian, living or dead,

00:51:13.480 --> 00:51:17.136
and he answered
"Probably John Nash."

00:51:17.136 --> 00:51:22.590
In 1994 as he had been out
of his mental condition,

00:51:22.590 --> 00:51:26.870
Nash was awarded a Nobel prize
in Economics for his PhD,

00:51:26.870 --> 00:51:31.740
for that two-page paper in which
he defined the Nash equilibria.

00:51:31.740 --> 00:51:32.890
Here is the situation.

00:51:32.890 --> 00:51:34.790
OK, you know it's not
really the Nobel prize.

00:51:34.790 --> 00:51:37.290
It's the Sveriges Riksbank
Prize in Economic Sciences

00:51:37.290 --> 00:51:40.670
in memory of Alfred Nobel,
awarded jointly to-- et cetera,

00:51:40.670 --> 00:51:43.540
et cetera-- including John Nash
"for their pioneering analysis

00:51:43.540 --> 00:51:47.180
of equilibria in the theory
of noncooperative games."

00:51:47.180 --> 00:51:52.180
Looked like Nash's genius
had been recognized at last.

00:51:52.180 --> 00:51:56.560
2001, it was the
movie Beautiful Mind.

00:51:56.560 --> 00:52:01.020
So this is Russell Crowe,
playing the role of Nash.

00:52:01.020 --> 00:52:02.940
I'm not sure he understands
anything of what's

00:52:02.940 --> 00:52:04.023
written on the blackboard.

00:52:04.023 --> 00:52:07.180
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:07.180 --> 00:52:09.020
I can recognize these
are the equations

00:52:09.020 --> 00:52:11.590
of isometric embedding.

00:52:11.590 --> 00:52:14.480
The film beautifully manages
to massacre everything

00:52:14.480 --> 00:52:15.470
in the life of Nash.

00:52:15.470 --> 00:52:16.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:16.270 --> 00:52:20.480
The chronology's wrong, the
nature of the mental condition

00:52:20.480 --> 00:52:24.890
is wrong, the nature of the
science contributions is wrong.

00:52:24.890 --> 00:52:26.270
It's amazing how
the film manages

00:52:26.270 --> 00:52:27.850
to get it wrong on all points.

00:52:27.850 --> 00:52:29.810
Brilliant.

00:52:29.810 --> 00:52:32.400
Nash hated every single
bit of the movie.

00:52:32.400 --> 00:52:38.225
But interestingly, his
wife-- his wife Alicia--

00:52:38.225 --> 00:52:43.330
found it was lovely to be played
onscreen by Hollywood beauty

00:52:43.330 --> 00:52:44.678
Jennifer Connelly.

00:52:44.678 --> 00:52:46.900
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:49.460 --> 00:52:51.910
Now, for
mathematicians, it still

00:52:51.910 --> 00:52:55.940
remained as a problem, you
know, that Nash's genius had

00:52:55.940 --> 00:52:58.020
been recognized in
economics but not

00:52:58.020 --> 00:53:01.980
for his truly beautiful
mathematical work related

00:53:01.980 --> 00:53:05.030
to the geometry and analysis.

00:53:05.030 --> 00:53:08.220
And little by little came
this public recognition.

00:53:08.220 --> 00:53:13.620
2009 was a big splash, when
Nash's ideas led Camillo De

00:53:13.620 --> 00:53:17.060
Lellis and Laszlo Szekelyhidi,
bright young mathematicians

00:53:17.060 --> 00:53:19.430
from Italy and
Hungary, respectively,

00:53:19.430 --> 00:53:22.860
to construct some impossible
solutions of Euler's equation--

00:53:22.860 --> 00:53:24.530
crazy solutions.

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:28.810
Imagine a fluid that would
be at rest initially,

00:53:28.810 --> 00:53:30.740
then start to
agitate like crazy,

00:53:30.740 --> 00:53:34.280
then be at rest again, without
any force acting on it.

00:53:34.280 --> 00:53:37.420
Something that made us
rethink the definition of what

00:53:37.420 --> 00:53:40.490
is a solution to
a fluid equation.

00:53:40.490 --> 00:53:43.875
In 2012, I depicted my
emotional encounter with Nash

00:53:43.875 --> 00:53:46.270
in "Birth of a Theorem."

00:53:46.270 --> 00:53:50.600
This was, like, autobiographical
book, or at least talking

00:53:50.600 --> 00:53:54.510
about how it is to
prove a theorem.

00:53:54.510 --> 00:53:59.030
All the ups and downs,
difficulties, mistakes,

00:53:59.030 --> 00:54:01.590
traveling, meeting
with people-- whatever.

00:54:01.590 --> 00:54:04.290
And one chapter is
devoted to my encounter

00:54:04.290 --> 00:54:08.870
with Nash in Princeton,
at the T. And I was so,

00:54:08.870 --> 00:54:11.400
you know-- he represented
so much to me.

00:54:11.400 --> 00:54:15.370
I was so, how to say,
impressed that I did not even

00:54:15.370 --> 00:54:19.710
dare to speak with him
on the first encounter.

00:54:19.710 --> 00:54:26.610
And 2015, Nash at last was
awarded the Abel Prize.

00:54:26.610 --> 00:54:30.550
Abel Prize is, together
with Fields Medal,

00:54:30.550 --> 00:54:33.176
for sure the most
prestigious prize.

00:54:33.176 --> 00:54:35.430
Abel Prize is certainly
more difficult to get

00:54:35.430 --> 00:54:36.890
than Fields Medal.

00:54:36.890 --> 00:54:42.370
Abel Prize is younger--
started, like, 15 years ago.

00:54:42.370 --> 00:54:45.330
Abel Prize typically
goes to the living,

00:54:45.330 --> 00:54:48.100
old legends in their 70s
who made contributions

00:54:48.100 --> 00:54:51.280
that everybody knows
and is amazed of.

00:54:51.280 --> 00:54:56.320
And I sat on the committee on
the Abel Prize, in those days.

00:54:56.320 --> 00:54:59.290
It was very emotional
for me, also,

00:54:59.290 --> 00:55:02.830
as being on that
committee the person

00:55:02.830 --> 00:55:05.570
who was scientifically
closest to Nash--

00:55:05.570 --> 00:55:10.470
you know, the one in charge
of defending the work of Nash.

00:55:10.470 --> 00:55:12.320
I will not say more
about the discussions,

00:55:12.320 --> 00:55:14.080
because, of course, it's secret.

00:55:14.080 --> 00:55:17.170
But this was very interesting
discussions we had about this.

00:55:17.170 --> 00:55:21.160
19 May 2015, in
Oslo, the Abel Prize

00:55:21.160 --> 00:55:24.230
was awarded jointly to John
Nash and Louis Nirenberg--

00:55:24.230 --> 00:55:27.500
you know, these guys, they
have a long history together--

00:55:27.500 --> 00:55:30.020
for striking and similar
contributions to the theory

00:55:30.020 --> 00:55:31.530
of nonlinear
partial differential

00:55:31.530 --> 00:55:36.250
equations and its applications
to geometric analysis.

00:55:36.250 --> 00:55:37.430
Very emotional moment.

00:55:37.430 --> 00:55:41.340
You have to imagine the
ceremony, also-- King of Norway

00:55:41.340 --> 00:55:46.070
was there, Nash gave
speech, and so on.

00:55:46.070 --> 00:55:52.730
There was public speech of Nash,
in which Nash recollected some

00:55:52.730 --> 00:55:55.750
of his older work,
some other work

00:55:55.750 --> 00:56:04.010
that he discussed with Einstein,
related to general relativity.

00:56:04.010 --> 00:56:06.160
I had the honor to
be his chairman.

00:56:06.160 --> 00:56:09.080
This was our fourth
encounter, actually.

00:56:09.080 --> 00:56:12.440
And for all the community,
everybody thought,

00:56:12.440 --> 00:56:15.870
at last-- Nash got this reward.

00:56:15.870 --> 00:56:18.900
And it was quite due.

00:56:18.900 --> 00:56:23.150
So it was the mood--
after this prize,

00:56:23.150 --> 00:56:26.070
he will at least-- he
can relax-- recognize,

00:56:26.070 --> 00:56:27.860
money, whatever.

00:56:27.860 --> 00:56:29.460
Not so.

00:56:29.460 --> 00:56:32.785
23 May 2015, back
from the ceremony,

00:56:32.785 --> 00:56:36.420
en route to Princeton, he
died, together with his wife,

00:56:36.420 --> 00:56:37.513
in a taxi crash.

00:56:40.900 --> 00:56:44.940
We met again with
Nirenberg, later on,

00:56:44.940 --> 00:56:47.160
trying to make sense
of it, whatever.

00:56:47.160 --> 00:56:52.270
Nirenberg [INAUDIBLE] Nash
ever did anything like anybody.

00:56:52.270 --> 00:56:53.700
Extra-terrestrian.

00:56:53.700 --> 00:56:57.760
Always gives these proofs that
no one can understand at first.

00:56:57.760 --> 00:57:02.590
He himself was unable to
explain them-- always saw things

00:57:02.590 --> 00:57:05.030
that people think is impossible.

00:57:05.030 --> 00:57:08.900
Gets Nobel Prize
for his PhD work,

00:57:08.900 --> 00:57:11.690
after having becoming
insane from an illness

00:57:11.690 --> 00:57:14.470
that you're supposed
never to recover.

00:57:14.470 --> 00:57:18.870
And, in the end, dies
like nobody else.

00:57:18.870 --> 00:57:22.630
Anyway, this is tragic.

00:57:22.630 --> 00:57:27.760
But the beauty of it, of
course, is the methods.

00:57:27.760 --> 00:57:31.050
And many mathematicians
feel that Nash

00:57:31.050 --> 00:57:34.690
is part of their family, in
the sense that he brought

00:57:34.690 --> 00:57:37.420
so many ideas and techniques.

00:57:37.420 --> 00:57:41.750
If I think of my own
work, I can see clearly

00:57:41.750 --> 00:57:43.880
relations with Nash's work.

00:57:43.880 --> 00:57:46.410
The taste
statistical-mechanics problems,

00:57:46.410 --> 00:57:49.150
the taste for
entropy, the key role

00:57:49.150 --> 00:57:52.130
of regularity-- which I
uncovered with my collaborators

00:57:52.130 --> 00:57:53.670
in similar problems.

00:57:53.670 --> 00:57:56.100
We, for instance,
in the problem that

00:57:56.100 --> 00:58:02.650
was one of my-- our--
most noticed papers,

00:58:02.650 --> 00:58:05.700
about behavior of
plasmas-- we uncovered

00:58:05.700 --> 00:58:09.330
how critical the role of
regularity was, in a way

00:58:09.330 --> 00:58:13.050
that had not been understood
before by physicists

00:58:13.050 --> 00:58:14.960
or mathematicians and this.

00:58:14.960 --> 00:58:18.540
And, also like Nash,
I admire his talent

00:58:18.540 --> 00:58:21.130
take pleasure in this sharp,
massive attack of given

00:58:21.130 --> 00:58:24.040
simple problem, in some
sense-- with simple and

00:58:24.040 --> 00:58:26.020
well-calibrating
tools, always trying

00:58:26.020 --> 00:58:28.220
to uncovering new connections.

00:58:28.220 --> 00:58:32.750
This idea, that idea, let's
put it together, and so on.

00:58:32.750 --> 00:58:36.850
And so, in a way, the Nash
legacy still lives on.

00:58:36.850 --> 00:58:39.910
And I will conclude with this.

00:58:39.910 --> 00:58:43.650
Putting on, flashing,
just this bibliography,

00:58:43.650 --> 00:58:47.140
recommending to you, by
the way, the Beautiful Mind

00:58:47.140 --> 00:58:51.580
book by Nasar-- well,
especially chapters 20, 30,

00:58:51.580 --> 00:58:56.070
31, in which you will find
the stories behind the scenes

00:58:56.070 --> 00:58:58.930
for the mathematical
achievements-- which,

00:58:58.930 --> 00:59:03.030
for us, is even much more
important than the mental

00:59:03.030 --> 00:59:05.170
in the story.

00:59:05.170 --> 00:59:08.760
Nash wrote four big
papers, you know.

00:59:08.760 --> 00:59:11.850
That's nothing, compared
to a big list of papers.

00:59:11.850 --> 00:59:14.710
But, of these four
papers, three,

00:59:14.710 --> 00:59:19.220
probably, in retrospect, would
have deserved the Fields Medal.

00:59:19.220 --> 00:59:25.700
On my web page, on my blog,
on date of 26 December 2015,

00:59:25.700 --> 00:59:29.450
you will also find, in
French, a short article--

00:59:29.450 --> 00:59:32.350
or not so short-- in
memoriam John Nash,

00:59:32.350 --> 00:59:36.300
entitled "Breve rencontre"--
"Brief Encounter."

00:59:36.300 --> 00:59:39.010
And, with this, I will
conclude this discourse.

00:59:39.010 --> 00:59:39.880
Thank you.

00:59:39.880 --> 00:59:41.430
[APPLAUSE]

